PURPORTThe divine vision in this connection should be clearly understood. Who can have divine vision? Divine means godly. Unless one attains the status of divinity as a demigod, he cannot have divine vision. And what is a demigod? It is stated in the Vedic scriptures that those who are devotees of Lord Vi\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9au are demigods. Those who are atheistic, i.e., who do not believe in Vi\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9au, or who only recognize the impersonal part of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa as the Supreme, cannot have the divine vision. It is not possible to decry K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa and at the same time have the \ndivine vision. One cannot have the divine vision without becoming divine. In other words, those who have divine vision can also see like Arjuna.The Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 gives the description of the universal form, and this description was unknown to everyone before Arjuna. Now one can have some idea of the after this incidence; those who are actually divine can see the universal form of the Lord. But one cannot be divine without being a pure devotee of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. The devotees, however, who are actually in the divine \nnature and who have divine vision, are not very much interested to see the universal form of the Lord. As described in the previous verse, Arjuna desired to see the four-handed form of Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa as Vi\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9au, and he was actually afraid of the universal form.In this verse there are some significant words, just like veda-yaj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92dhya-yanai\xc5\xa1, which refers to studying Vedic literature and the subject matter of sacrificial \nregulations. Veda refers to all kinds of Vedic literature, namely the four Vedas (\xe2\x80\xa0k, Yajus, S\xe2\x88\x92ma and Atharva) and the eighteen Pur\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9aas and Upani\xc5\x92ads, and One can study these at home or anywhere else. Similarly, there are and for studying the method of sacrifice. D\xe2\x88\x92nai\xc5\xa1 refers to charity which is offered to a suitable party. such as those who are engaged in the transcendental loving service of the Lord, the br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aas and the Vai\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aavas. Similarly, pious activities refer to the agni-hotra, etc., the prescribed duties of the different castes. Pious activities and the \nvoluntary acceptance of some bodily pains are called tapasya. So one can perform all these, can accept bodily penances, give charity, study the Vedas, etc., but unless he is a devotee like Arjuna, it is not possible to see that \nuniversal form. Those who are impersonalists are also imagining that they are seeing the universal form of the Lord, but from Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 we understand '
b'that the impersonalists are not devotees. Therefore they are unable to see the universal form of the Lord.There are many persons who create incarnations. They falsely claim an ordinary human to be an incarnation, but this is all foolishness. We should follow the principles of Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92, otherwise there is no possibility of attaining perfect spiritual knowledge. Although Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 is considered the preliminary study of the science of God, still it is so perfect that one can distinguish what is what. The followers of a pseudo incarnation may say that \nthey have also seen the transcendental incarnation of God, the universal form, but that is not acceptable because it is clearly stated here that unless one becomes a devotee of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, one cannot see the universal form of God. So one first of all has to become a pure devotee of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa; then he can claim that he can show the universal form of what he has seen. A devotee of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa cannot accept false incarnations or followers of false incarnations.
